###### Proposition 4.11.

A height function \mu induces a strong matroidal subdivision of 2\_{21} if and only if \mu\in\operatorname{Dr}(E\_{6},P\_{1}).

* Proof.

  One direction follows from affine invariance. For the other, let f\_{\Diamond} correspond to a D\_{5} cross polytope \Diamond in the 5-skeleton of 2\_{21}, and consider the restriction of the subdivision induced by \mu to \Diamond. If the minimum on f\_{\Diamond} were unique, Proposition 4.6 tells us that there is a maximal cell of the restriction with peerless antipodes (A,B). Since all possible peers for (A,B) in 2\_{21} correspond to entries of f\_{\Diamond}, (A,B) form peerless antipodes of some maximal cell in the global subdivision. The result follows from the contrapositive.
  ∎

### 4.6. Type E\_{7}

